SUMMARY.

Tne fourth book contains three episodes-the war with the Usipetes and Tencteri, the first passage oi the Rhine and the first invasion oi Britain, besides some operatione against the Morini and Menapii.

The Usipetes and Tencteri were two German tribes which suffered like others from the overwhelming power ol the vast confederation ol the Suebi. Dislodged from their own abodes, they wandered lor three years in many pairs oi Germany, and at last came to the Rhine‚ not far from where it flows into the sea. The Menapii dwelt in these parts and had possessione on both sides os the river. They retired before the invaders to the leit bank, which they were able to hold against them. Despairing of accomplishing their passage by force, the Usipetes and Tencteri had recourse to fraud. They retired a three days' joumey from the Rhine, and when the Menapii had msumed their possessione on the right bank, they sent their cavalry back by night, who surprised the Menapii, and possessed themselves os their vessels. After this the whole body ol invaders established themselves on the Gallie side os the river.
